<p>A typical 6kW residential solar system in Georgia can be expected to produce between 7,500 and 8,500 kWh annually, depending on specific location, panel orientation, and system efficiency. South-facing installations with optimal tilt angles of 32-35 degrees achieve maximum production, though east and west-facing systems still provide excellent returns. The state's relatively moderate temperatures during peak solar months help maintain panel efficiency, as excessive heat can reduce photovoltaic performance. Georgia's solar production capacity remains strong even during partly cloudy conditions, thanks to advanced panel technology that can capture diffused sunlight effectively.</p>

