<h2>HVAC Systems in Georgia</h2>
<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Georgia's humid subtropical climate creates specific demands for HVAC systems that must efficiently handle both cooling and dehumidification during the extended warm season while providing adequate heating during brief but sometimes intense cold periods. The state experiences approximately 2,500-3,500 cooling degree days annually and 1,500-3,000 heating degree days, with cooling representing roughly 60-70% of annual HVAC energy consumption for most homes. This cooling-dominated climate makes high-efficiency air conditioning systems essential for managing energy costs, particularly during July and August when temperatures regularly exceed 90¬∞F with high humidity levels.</p>

<p>For optimal performance in Georgia's climate, HVAC systems should feature SEER ratings of at least 16-18, with higher ratings providing better long-term savings despite increased upfront costs. Heat pump systems are particularly well-suited to Georgia's moderate winter conditions, providing efficient heating when temperatures remain above 25¬∞F, which covers the vast majority of winter days across the state. Variable-speed compressors and advanced humidity control features become crucial for maintaining comfort while managing the high moisture content typical of Georgia's air, especially in coastal regions where humidity levels can remain elevated even during cooler months.</p>

