<h2>Georgia Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>Georgia offers several attractive incentives that make solar panel and HVAC system installations more affordable for homeowners. The most significant benefit comes from the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which allows homeowners to deduct 30% of the total solar installation cost from their federal taxes. This credit applies to the full system cost, including equipment, installation, and associated electrical work, with no cap on the credit amount. The 30% rate remains in effect through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034 before expiring for residential installations.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> The most valuable incentive available, this credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds your current tax liability. For a typical \$24,000 solar installation, this provides \$7,200 in tax credits. The credit applies to solar panels, inverters, mounting equipment, installation labor, and any electrical work necessary to connect the system.</li>
<li><strong>State Property Tax Exemption:</strong> Georgia provides a complete exemption from property tax increases for residential solar installations. While your solar system may increase your home's value by \$15,000-\$20,000, you won't pay additional property taxes on this increased value, saving hundreds of dollars annually in many counties.</li>
<li><strong>Georgia Power Solar Buyback Program:</strong> Under net metering arrangements, Georgia Power customers receive credit for excess solar energy fed back into the grid at avoided cost rates. While lower than retail rates, this program ensures that all solar production provides economic value to homeowners.</li>
<li><strong>Local Utility Rebates:</strong> Many Georgia electric membership corporations (EMCs) offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC systems and solar installations. These rebates typically range from \$200-\$1,000 for qualifying heat pumps and air conditioning systems with SEER ratings of 16 or higher.</li>
<li><strong>USDA Rural Development Grants:</strong> Rural Georgia homeowners may qualify for USDA grants covering up to 25% of solar installation costs, with maximum grants of \$10,000. These grants can be combined with federal tax credits for maximum savings.</li>
</ul>

